The types for your table column are always the type of the item in each row (i.e. the same as the type you use for the table view) for the first type parameter, and the type of the (current) value for each cell in the column for the second parameter. So if your table view has type `TableViewTest`, and your combo box is selecting `String`s, you should have:

    TableColumn&lt;TableViewTest, String&gt; priceColumn ;

The cell value factory should still map to a property in the `TableViewTest` class, i.e. assuming you have:

    public class TableViewTest {

        // ...

        public StringProperty priceProperty() {
            // ...
        }

        // ...
    }

then you can do:

    priceColumn.setCellValueFactory(new PropertyValueFactory&lt;&gt;(&quot;price&quot;));

or (much better):

    priceColumn.setCellValueFactory(cellData -&gt; cellData.getValue().priceProperty());

